benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/auditLogs - Retrieve audit logs by account id

covered: Valid Request: TC01 verifies successful retrieval with 200, Content-Type application/json and that the body is a JSON array of AuditLog objects (presence of required fields).
Empty Response: TC02 and TC12 validate the service returns an empty JSON array (200) when no audit logs exist.
Error responses: TC03 (404 for non-existent account), TC08 (500 for internal errors), and TC11 (503/504 for timeouts/service unavailable) cover expected error status codes.
Input validation & security: TC04 (malformed UUID), TC10 (injection attempt), and TC15 (empty accountId) cover bad/invalid path inputs and input rejection.
Authorization: TC05 and TC06 check missing and invalid authentication tokens (401 scenarios).
Query parameter tolerance: TC07 verifies extra/unexpected query parameters are ignored.
Scale/performance & concurrency: TC09 tests a very large result set (10,000 items) and response time; TC14 verifies behavior under 100 concurrent requests.
Regression & backward compatibility: TC12 ensures a previously fixed bug (empty audit logs returning 500) does not regress; TC13 covers an older client scenario.
gaps: Pagination: No tests exercise pagination parameters (limit/offset/page) or pagination response headers (Link, total-count, page-size) — TC09 checks large volume but does not verify paginated responses.

Rate limiting / throttling: There are no tests that assert rate limiting behavior (429 responses) or the system behavior when request bursts exceed configured limits. TC14 concurrency is not the same as rate-limit testing.
Caching behavior & conditional GETs: No scenarios validate caching headers (ETag, Last-Modified, Cache-Control) or conditional requests (If-None-Match / 304 responses).

Authorization scope/permissions: Tests check missing/invalid tokens (401) but do not cover permission/authorization failures (403) — e.g., a valid user without rights to view another accountâ€™s audit logs.

Schema/detail validation: TC01 asserts required fields exist but there are no explicit schema tests verifying field types, formats, nullable rules, or exact required properties as defined by the API definition.
Response headers / content negotiation: Tests do not verify other important headers (e.g., Content-Length, caching headers) or behavior for different Accept headers (content negotiation).
Rate / load boundaries & error consistency: Large-scale behavior is only one scenario (10k items); boundary values (page size limits) and consistent error payload shapes are not asserted.
recommendations: Add pagination scenarios: include tests for limit/offset or page & pageSize parameters, assert pagination headers (Link, total-count), and validate correct slicing of results and boundary conditions (page 0, last page, page beyond range).
Add rate-limiting tests: simulate bursts and sustained high-frequency requests to assert 429 responses and verify Retry-After behavior where applicable.
Add caching/conditional GET tests: verify ETag and Last-Modified are returned on GET, then call with If-None-Match/If-Modified-Since to confirm 304 Not Modified responses when appropriate.
Expand authorization tests: add scenarios for valid tokens with insufficient permissions (expect 403), and tests for multi-tenant access control (user A attempting to access user Bâ€™s account logs).

Tighten schema validation: add tests that validate each AuditLog object against the official schema (field presence, types, formats, required/optional fields) and assert consistent error payload structure for failures.
Add content-negotiation and header checks: test different Accept headers, Content-Length correctness, and important response headers (Cache-Control, ETag, Connection).
Add pagination + large dataset combination: verify performance and correctness when paginating very large result sets (e.g., fetching page-by-page) and assert acceptable response times for each page.
Add rate/limit & retry policy regression tests: ensure behavior remains stable across releases and that retry hints (Retry-After) are honored by clients.
